pullRequest.body:
We show that a holomorphic function which is periodic with a real period `h` is given by `f z = F (exp (2 * pi * I * z / h))` for some holomorphic `F`, and moreover, if `f` is bounded as `Im z -> infty` then `F` extends holomorphically to `q = 0`. 

---

Should these not be camelCase?
yes I was going to suggest `qParam`. I'm actually doing some of these changes now and will add them as a review.
Does "fcn" mean something?
It was intended as shorthand for "function". I'd be happy to rename if there's something else which fits better.
How about ... "function"?
Sorry, my last post was very unclear; I meant that there might be better alternatives than "cuspFunction" or abbreviations thereof.
:bulb: :+1:

```suggestion
theorem differentiableAt_cuspFcn (hh : h â‰  0) (hf : Periodic f h)
```

```suggestion
theorem differentiableAt_cuspFcn_zero (hh : 0 < h) (hf : Periodic f h)
```

```suggestion
theorem qParam_right_inv (hh : h â‰  0) {e : â„‚} (hq : e â‰  0) : ð•¢ h (invQParam h e) = e := by
```
Do we want to also have a DifferentiableOn version? (given the section is called HoloOnC).

I'm not sure. I can't really imagine settings in modular form theory where we would care about a `DifferentiableWithinAt` statement, or a `DifferentiableOn` for a set which isn't open. 

(Please don't read too much into the section name, that has survived unchanged from literally the first Lean code file I ever wrote!)

There are also multiple possible formulations of a `DifferentiableOn` statement -- taking fwd / inverse image of a set under `qParam` or `invQParam` -- and it would be a pain to untangle which are true, and which of the true ones are useful. I suggest we wait, and see if any of them come up in practice as we work out more q-expansion theory.
Sure I think thats sensible!
Change `hq` to `he`? There is no variable `q` around.

```suggestion
  exact differentiableAt_cuspFunction hh.ne' hf h_diff
```

```suggestion
  suffices cuspFunction h f =O[_] id by
    simpa only [comp_def, eq_cuspFunction hh.ne' hf, id_eq, norm_eq_abs, abs_qParam]
      using (this.comp_tendsto (qParam_tendsto hh)).norm_right
```
for easier reading...
